      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        How an Expressions of Interest Campaign Works When Selling Brisbane Property
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Expressions of interest campaigns give sellers control over the offer process without the pressure of a public auction. Here is how they work and when they are the right choice.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>When people think about selling a property, they typically imagine either a private treaty sale with a listed asking price, or a public auction where buyers bid openly. There is a third method that sits between these two and is increasingly common for higher-value or less-typical properties in Brisbane's inner east: an expressions of interest campaign, often referred to as an EOI.</p>

      <p>An EOI campaign is not well understood by most vendors. Many assume it is just an auction without the auctioneer, or a fancy name for private treaty. It is neither. Understanding how it actually works, and when your agent is likely to recommend it, will help you make a better decision about your sale method.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What an EOI campaign actually is</h2>
      <p>In an expressions of interest campaign, buyers submit written offers by a specified deadline. The submission is confidential: each buyer submits their offer without knowing what others have offered. There is no public bidding, no auctioneer, and no visible competition between buyers. After the deadline, the seller reviews all submissions and decides how to proceed.</p>

      <p>The key distinction from private treaty is the controlled deadline. With private treaty, buyers can submit offers at any point and negotiations can drag out over weeks. With EOI, the deadline creates urgency and concentrates buyer interest into a single decision point for the seller.</p>

      <p>The key distinction from auction is the absence of public, visible competition. At an auction, buyers see each other and bid against each other in real time. In an EOI, each buyer submits their best offer independently, based on their own assessment of the property's value, without the emotional pressure of public bidding.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When agents recommend EOI over auction or private treaty</h2>
      <p>Your agent will typically recommend an EOI campaign in several circumstances. The most common is when the property is difficult to appraise with precision, usually because it is unusual in some way: a large land holding, a property with significant development potential, a heritage home, or a property with a unique configuration that limits direct comparable sales.</p>

      <p>EOI is also often recommended when the likely buyer pool is sophisticated and may prefer the privacy of a written submission process over the public theatre of an auction. Some buyers, particularly those in the corporate, professional, or interstate categories, are more comfortable submitting a considered written offer than bidding publicly. An EOI process accommodates this preference without reducing competitive tension.</p>

      <p>For properties in Brisbane's inner east, EOI campaigns tend to work well for character Queenslanders on large blocks, premium riverfront or elevated properties, and architect-designed homes where the value is genuinely difficult to establish through comparable sales alone. For more standard three or four bedroom homes in established suburbs with plentiful comparable sales, private treaty or auction will usually serve the seller better.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The EOI process step by step</h2>
      <p>An EOI campaign has a clear structure. The marketing period typically runs for three to four weeks, matching the duration of a standard auction campaign. During this period, the property is presented to the market through the same channels as any other sale: photography, floor plans, online listings, open homes, and targeted outreach to buyer databases.</p>

      <p>Buyers who are interested in submitting a formal offer are given an information memorandum, which includes contract documentation, any relevant property information, and the submission requirements. The submission typically requires buyers to specify their offered purchase price, proposed settlement date, deposit amount, and any conditions. Many EOI campaigns are conducted on an unconditional basis, meaning the seller expects offers without finance or building and pest clauses.</p>

      <p>On the submission deadline, the agent collects all offers and presents them to the seller. The seller then has several options: accept the highest or most favourable offer, enter into private negotiation with one or more shortlisted buyers, or if no offer is satisfactory, decline all submissions and re-list. Unlike an auction, the seller is not obligated to sell on the day.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How sellers evaluate EOI offers</h2>
      <p>Price is the primary factor but not always the only one. In a competitive EOI where multiple offers are close in price, the seller and agent will look carefully at the other terms. A higher price with a lengthy settlement period, a large number of special conditions, or a buyer who appears uncertain may be less attractive than a slightly lower offer that is clean, unconditional, and from a buyer who is clearly ready to proceed.</p>

      <p>Settlement date can be a meaningful differentiator. If you are buying simultaneously and need a specific settlement timeline, an offer that aligns with your needs has real value beyond its headline price. Your agent should understand your situation well enough to factor this into the evaluation conversation.</p>

      <p>The deposit amount proposed can also signal buyer commitment. A buyer offering a larger deposit at exchange is typically more serious about completing the transaction than one proposing the minimum. In a situation where you are choosing between similar offers, this is worth weighing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The advantages of an EOI campaign</h2>
      <p>Privacy is one of the most cited reasons vendors choose EOI. The process is not publicly listed as an auction, which can matter to some vendors who prefer not to broadcast the sale timeline or the competitive dynamics of their campaign. For properties in sensitive price brackets or with vendor circumstances that call for discretion, this matters.</p>

      <p>The controlled timeline is another advantage. Unlike private treaty, where buyers can sit on a decision or negotiate slowly, an EOI deadline encourages buyers to form a view and commit to a number. This benefits sellers by concentrating decision-making and reducing the drawn-out negotiation that can characterise longer private treaty campaigns.</p>

      <p>The ability to negotiate with multiple parties simultaneously, without those parties being aware of each other, is also an advantage EOI offers that auction does not. After reviewing submissions, you can go back to two or three serious buyers separately and invite revised offers before making a final decision. This post-deadline negotiation phase is common and can produce a stronger result than the initial submissions alone.</p>

      <p>For sellers who are uncomfortable with the public nature of an auction but want more discipline and urgency than private treaty provides, EOI often strikes the right balance.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Brisbane inner east properties where EOI works well</h2>
      <p>In the inner east suburbs served by this agency, EOI tends to produce strong results for a specific type of property. Character Queenslanders on large blocks in Camp Hill, Coorparoo, and Morningside, where the combination of land size and home character creates a value proposition that is difficult to benchmark precisely, are natural EOI candidates. Premium elevated properties in Hawthorne and Bulimba with river views or a strong renovation outcome are another category where EOI concentrates serious buyer interest effectively.</p>

      <p>For more straightforward family homes in suburbs with regular comparable sales, your agent will usually recommend auction or private treaty. The additional complexity of an EOI campaign is only justified when the property genuinely benefits from the structured process. If your agent recommends EOI, ask them to explain specifically why they think it is the right method for your property and what the comparable EOI results in your suburb look like.</p>

